Reflecting on another trip around the sun, I never anticipated being in the place I find myself today, but I'm sincerely grateful just to be alive. The past several months have brought a multitude of changes in every aspect of my life. My biggest hurdle has been navigating change, as fear seeps in. Will I be alright? Can I overcome this? However, amidst it all, I am immensely thankful for this chapter. I hold nothing but love for it—the moments, the blessings, the setbacks, the good and the bad days. The more I began to accept this, I began to see magical changes in my life. It’s okay to be a work in progress, everyday is a step forward..and whether it’s a small or large step, the motion is still forward. Reminding myself that the most courageous thing you can do is love yourself. To love yourself through all the cracks and dents that life sometimes leave you with. It's about falling repeatedly and finding the strength to rise again. Love unconditionally, without inhibitions, and be a little delulu, or a lot, who cares! As I enter the new year, I honor the past one, with my heart wide open ready to rediscover myself, to foster old and new friendships, to love, to new experiences, and to reaffirm the belief that life is truly worth living 🦀 🌊

Let’s begin by saying I’ve always had the desire to learn how to surf and live out my Blue Crush dreams, no matter how cliché it may sound. I kept pushing it aside because, well, I thought it wasn’t the most productive use of my time. To pursue something purely for the sake of enjoyment? What is the return on the cost, effort and time spent, especially when taking into account my genuine fear of the ocean and my limited swimming abilities?

Earlier this year, I went on a solo trip, and my only goal was to learn how to surf. I wanted to know what it felt like to stand up on a wave. I reached out to several surf schools, and one of them told me I shouldn’t bother if I was scared. It felt discouraging and made me feel embarrassed to even want to try 😭

However, I came across @mickeysurfschool, took my initial lessons there, and promised I’d be back later this year for more comprehensive learning. Fast forward to today, I’ve been learning from @isaiahmoniz @oahusurfschool for the past weeks. After each surf sesh, I feel sad it’s over. My heart wants to stay out even though my arms feel like noodles. It’s been a magical journey of gradual progress, and I can’t help but feel soooooooo happy with how far I’ve come in facing my fears. Day by day, I’m feeling more confident and at ease, and it’s just so amazing to find something that fills my heart with as much joy as surfing does 🥹❤️

So, if you’re ever considering taking up surfing and you’re looking for a highly supportive community to learn from, I wholeheartedly recommend Mickey and Isaiah.

I was initially hesitant to share this because I worried about appearing ridiculous, having imperfect form, and missing some steps at the end... but I wanted to share with you, if there’s something you aspire to pursue, even if it seems silly or embarrassing, don’t let self-doubt hinder your progress. You have complete control over your limitations! Consider this your reminder to step out of your comfort zone!

As for the cost, effort, and time I mentioned earlier, it was sooooooo worth it, and I wish I did it sooner.

While 2023 comes to a close, I find myself reflecting on what has undeniably been one of the most challenging yet resilient years of my life. Having to navigate the aftermath of being laid off from a position where I poured my heart and soul (literally) felt like the world crumbling around me. 

Yet, amid the challenges, I discovered a silver lining—the most powerful blessing of my life. Learning to love myself again became a priority. I had to rebuild and regain confidence. Holding myself accountable for aspirations I’d long talked about—like learning to surf and drive—became a beacon of resilience. I feel like I’m finally moving forward.

While 2023 has been a journey of ups and downs, it has paved the way for personal growth. I am proud of how far I’ve come. As I look ahead, 2024 is on the horizon, and I’m more than ready for the next chapter. 

Thank you to everyone who’s been there for me this year. I know I’ve been a little delulu and depressy 🥹🤍
In the past few months, I’ve danced with sunsets, tasted the hues of rainbows, and embraced the magic of each sunrise. Feeling so grateful ❤️🌈☀️
Lounging desert-side in Joshua Tree with @lpa @tracymarietassill 🌵

As a reminder to myself, I’m taking this time to just breathe and figure out what’s next. It’s okay not to know where that is or not be where I thought I would be by now. I’m learning to ride this wave and flow with it. I spent a lot of time these past few months beating myself up over not being ‘productive’ enough during this supposed rest period. Being in Hawai’i taught me the beauty of island time— to embrace the present and flow with the uncertainty. My friend Sam said to me, “If can, can. If no can, no can.”

For anyone who needs to hear this: rest is not a reward. You don’t have to earn rest; you need it. It’s perfectly okay and absolutely necessary and you are worthy. Love you 🤍

The meaning of being alive…is just being alive.

2023 was a transformative year that reshaped the very essence of my existence. The journey’s far from over – it’s an ever-unfolding path, a lifelong marathon, not a sprint.

I spent so much time beating myself up over not being my usual overproductive self this year. I craved rest and only wanted to do things that sparked joy. I wanted to put me first! For! Once! In! My! Life! It feels so silly because I always tell everyone around me to put themselves first, yet I’m the biggest hypocrite. The guilt was always there and even till this day my dad doesn’t even know that I took time off to reset. I didn’t want him to think I wouldn’t be able to support him or make him worry. I wanted to just handle things quietly with a smile on my face.

Looking back, I didn’t give myself credit for still showing up and still being here. That in itself is such a huge accomplishment. I was so sad, and it was a heavy weight to carry around. I didn’t realize how long I was in survival mode for. I need to and will forgive myself for what I had to do and who I had to be when I was still living in survival mode. I was in constant fight-or-flight, and it affected my mental and physical health tremendously. And it was in solitude and quiet that I rediscovered the simple joy of just being. I was able to better show up for myself and others. And this is something I have to practice everyday. 

We can get there together. Thank you for being here and reading up until this point.
